|}

After the outbreak of this uprising against [[Imperial Russia|Russia]], the Polish [[Sejm]] decreed on February 19, 1831 that the decoration be restored to its original name, the "Order Virtuti Militari."  Between March 3 and October the same year, 3,863 crosses were awarded. Recipients of the Silver Cross included three women:
* head [[surgery|surgeon]] of the 10th Line Infantry Regiment, [[J<U+00F3>zefa Kluczycka]];
* surgeon's assistant in the 10th Line Infantry Regiment, [[J<U+00F3>zefa Daniel|J<U+00F3>zefa Daniel Rostowska n<U+00E9>e Mazurkiewicz]]; and
* cadet in the 1st "[[August<U+00F3>w]]" Cavalry Regiment, [[Bronis<U+0142>awa Czarnowska]].

After the defeat of the uprising, Tsar Nicholas I abolished the decoration and banned its use. On December 31 1831, it was replaced with the "Polish Sign of Honor" (''Polski Znak Honorowy''), an exact copy of the original cross but awarded only to Russians for services to the Tsarist authorities.

